# From Beanstalk source to a webpage

This series provides educational scaffolding for a later writing pass. It
explains compiler concepts through one Beanstalk project. It does not define
compiler behaviour or current implementation status.

## Reader promise

- Follow one project from source files to generated HTML.
- Learn each compiler term when the running example needs it.
- Track which owner creates each representation.
- Separate accepted design from current, queued and deferred work.

## Running example

Project tree:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
compiler_walkthrough/
├── config.bst
└── src/
    ├── #page.bst
    └── greeting.bst
]

Keep these source shapes stable across the series:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
-- greeting.bst

greeting_prefix #= "Hello"

greet |name String| -> String:
    return [: [greeting_prefix], [name]!]
;
]

[codeblock, $code("text"):
-- #page.bst

import @greeting { greet }

visitor = "Priya"

[$html:
    <p>[greet(visitor)]</p>
]
]

Final relevant fragment:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
<p>Hello, Priya!</p>
]

## Pipeline position

Plan one reusable strip with these checkpoints:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
project tree
-> command and config
-> canonical source graph
-> located tokens
-> prepared shells
-> bound interfaces and ordered declarations
-> typed AST and semantic identities
-> folded constants, generated requests and TIR handoff
-> structured diagnostics
-> validated HIR
-> borrow and ownership side-table facts
-> immutable module artefacts and fingerprints
-> entry assembly and reachable function union
-> deterministic target assignment
-> JavaScript and Wasm outputs
-> HTML, runtime assets and output manifest
]

Outline each article around the current checkpoint. Show both the incoming
representation and the outgoing representation.

## Owners to introduce

- **Build system:** selects commands, discovers source, constructs graphs,
  schedules modules, plans entries and owns output writing.
- **Compiler frontend and analysis:** prepares syntax, binds interfaces,
  checks semantics, lowers HIR and validates access.
- **Artefact builder:** assembles selected compiler facts into an output plan.
- **Target backends:** lower validated functions and runtime requirements into
  JavaScript, Wasm and glue artefacts.

